post_text:
Cal-Mum Community...Superintendent of Schools Robert Molisani is asking for your help.
Currently, Governor Cuomo is withholding 20% of all State aid from school districts. It is his and our hope that the Federal government will provide funding to offset the fallen revenues due to combatting the pandemic.

For the Caledonia-Mumford Central School District, withholding 20% of state aid equates to $2.2 million dollars. Without a multi-year federal financial assistance plan to stabilize school funding, public schools in New York will be devastated.

Please view Mr. Molisani's message, contact your legislators and ask them to support public schools.

Once again, your help and support is necessary to prevent the destruction of public schools in New York. Thank you for your support.

Labor Day- the first Monday in September, is dedicated to the achievements of the American worker and their contributions to the strength, prosperity, and well-being of our country.
In many parts of the country, it also signals the end of summer vacation for millions of school children and the excitement of a new school year.
Like no other September in history, we anticipate welcoming our students to the 2020-2021 school year in just three days.
Enjoy your Labor Day!

post_text:
Fifty-seven years ago today, Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. delivered his historic "I Have a Dream Speech."
Fifty-seven years later we continue our work toward achieving Dr. King's dream, but we are not there yet.
Caledonia-Mumford CSD is mindful of our responsibility as educators and leaders, of our goal to provide every student a safe and equitable education and school environment.
Let us continue the work that must be done - the work spoken of in Dr. King's, "I Have a Dream" speech.

"Let us not wallow in the valley of despair, I say to you today, my friends.
And so even though we face the difficulties of today and tomorrow, I still have a dream. It is a dream deeply rooted in the American dream.
I have a dream that one day this nation will rise up and live out the true meaning of its creed: We hold these truths to be self-evident, that all men are created equal."

Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.'s speech can be read and or listened to here: https://kinginstitute.stanford.edu/king-papers/documents/i-have-dream-address-delivered-march-washington-jobs-and-freedom

post_text:
Sometimes on Friday's, it's fun to flashback...today we are looking back to August 2012. The Walther family, John (PE teacher) and Diana (Byron-Bergen teacher), had recently welcomed their twin son & daughter into the world...however, the twins arrived far too early and while mom and dad were out of state in a mountain cabin on vacation. It was a frightening time for the Walthers and the Red Raider family wanted to help. School and community volunteers hosted a fundraiser to help with the very high cost of the medical transport to bring the twins from the out of state hospital where they were born to Golisano's Children's Hospital in Rochester where their parents could remain by their side.
The fundraiser drew hundreds of people from all over the area and John and Diana were truly grateful for the love and support of the Red Raider family, the Cal-Mum community, and of those they hadn't even met before.
The twins were safely transported back to Rochester and 8 years later we are happy to say they are healthy and happy third graders!

Flashback Friday - This takes us back to the heydays of the Caledonia Fair. Our students showed their best farm animals, domestic arts, and horticulture exhibits. Many of our students competed in the various equestrian events and the draft horse show.
The Caledonia Fair milking contest was always a favorite event. Thankfully, the Stein children offered quick training for Ms. Santora and CMCS Board of Ed.'s Tim Anderson who managed to be on the winning team.
For four days in August, the Caledonia Fairgrounds was home to many of our Red Raider families.
Enjoy these photo memories.

post_text:
It is with great sadness that we announce the passing away earlier this week of our former Caledonia-Mumford Elementary School Principal, Dr. Gerald Benjamin, affectionately known as Dr. Ben.

Dr. Ben was principal of the elementary school from 1990 – 1997. He was beloved by his students, parents, staff and the community for his warm personality, bright smile and infectious laugh. Dr. Ben loved children and was deeply committed to educating the whole child, including their social and emotional wellness.

Following his retirement from Caledonia-Mumford CSD, he spent 19 years as principal of St. Agnes Catholic Elementary School in Avon, NY.

Our thoughts and prayers are with the family and friends of Dr. Benjamin at this sad time.
Photo courtesy of a former St. Agnes student

With so many summer events canceled, we are really excited to share with you a unique activity that you and your family and friends will enjoy.
It's called Livingston County Inspirations Trail, a self-guided art tour through nine Livingston County downtowns.
We are very proud to say that the Caledonia downtown artwork includes several pieces from our students as well as some from Adventures and Art.
The Inspirations Trail was put on hold until the summer of 2021due to Covid-19, however, the artwork that was already finished is on exhibit this summer until July 31, so don't delay - get out and take a walk around Caledonia's business district to see our students' artwork and take a ride to our neighboring villages to see others.
The Inspirations Trail website has all of the details.
https://inspirationstrail.com/sidewalk-showcase

post_text:
At last night’s meeting, John Bickford and Elizabeth Doll were sworn in as members of the Caledonia-Mumford CSD Board of Education. They will each serve a three-year term.
Mr. Bickford is entering his 11th term and 28th year on the board. Mrs. Doll is entering her 4th term and seventh year on the board.
Mr. Bickford was unanimously voted to the office of board president and Mr. Christopher Richter was unanimously voted to the office of board vice-president.
The board of education members thanked Mr. Arnold Rychlicki for having served as the vice-president for the past six years. Mr. Rychlicki will continue to serve the remainder of his term as a board of education member.
Thank you to all of the members of the Caledonia-Mumford CSD Board of Education for their service and commitment to our children’s education.
And enjoy the photo from 1997 with then School Board President Mr. Richard Riggi congratulating Mr. John Bickford.

On Thursday, July 9, 2020, at 8:15 a.m., the Cal-Mum School District sent out a Blackboard mass communication via phone and email. The topic was to ask parents to complete an online survey about reopening schools in September.

post_text: 155 years ago today, June 19, 1865, slavery, the enslavement of black Americans, was finally ended. More than two years after President Lincoln’s Emancipation Proclamation - which had become official January 1, 1863. This day is commemorated by the celebration called Juneteenth!
text: 155 years ago today, June 19, 1865, slavery, the enslavement of black Americans, was finally ended. More than two years after President Lincoln’s Emancipation Proclamation - which had become official January 1, 1863. This day is commemorated by the celebration called Juneteenth!

post_text:
Today, June 19, 2020, our nation celebrates the 155 year anniversary of the emancipation of black Americans - the end of slavery in the United States of America.
The celebration is called Juneteenth. Dating back to 1865, it was on June 19, 1865 that the Union soldiers, led by Major General Gordon Granger, landed at Galveston, Texas with news that the war had ended and that the enslaved were now free. Note that this was two and a half years after President Lincoln’s Emancipation Proclamation - which had become official January 1, 1863.
For those who do not know what Juneteenth is, we hope that you will take time today to learn about June 19, 1865, a landmark day in Black American history - and a day for all Americans to celebrate life and liberty. Google has done a great video tribute.
https://youtu.be/GNEPwwv56DY

post_text:
Elementary School Art teacher Mrs. Cassidy-Schaffer had a fun Flag Day project for you.

As artists, it is our job to communicate our thoughts and ideas on the world around us through visual images. The stars and stripes of our American Flag have been re-imagined by artists many times throughout history. The flag itself has even been re-imagined and changed since its original version in 1777. During this season of Flag Day and upcoming 4th of July, I challenge you to re-imagine the stars and stripes! How could you rearrange them? Would you add more symbols, colors, patterns? What materials would you create with? Check out the resources and art video at: https://sites.google.com/cal-mum.org/cmesartistunite/drawingart-videos#h.vpyp7twlqmep
text:
Elementary School Art teacher Mrs. Cassidy-Schaffer had a fun Flag Day project for you.

As artists, it is our job to communicate our thoughts and ideas on the world around us through visual images. The stars and stripes of our American Flag have been re-imagined by artists many times throughout history. The flag itself has even been re-imagined and changed since its original version in 1777. During this season of Flag Day and upcoming 4th of July, I challenge you to re-imagine the stars and stripes! How could you rearrange them? Would you add more symbols, colors, patterns? What materials would you create with? Check out the resources and art video at: https://sites.google.com/cal-mum.org/cmesartistunite/drawingart-videos#h.vpyp7twlqmep

post_text:
Sunday, June 14, 2020 is Flag Day. Normally, we would invite the community to join us at the elementary school for our Flag Day ceremony, led by the Matthew Cleary Post 255 American Legion Color Guard.
Flag Day commemorates the adoption of the flag of the United States on June 14, 1777 by resolution of the Second Continental Congress.
Our students and teachers have created a Flag Day video for you to enjoy.
We thank our guest speaker, 2016 Cal-Mum Alumnus Joshua Roides.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1gZgxkJYWsDBLx_BFeD9vIs6viyN9wIY4/view?ts=5ee151d9

Missing out on seeing friends and having them sign your yearbook? Jostens yearbook company has created a digital yearbook signing platform that will give you a printable permanent keepsake.

Check it out here: https://yearbooksigning.jostens.com/

Follow the instructions to register in a few easy steps. You’ll create a password and then get a link that you can share with trusted friends. DO NOT MAKE THE LINK PUBLIC. Friends will be able to create fun messages and you’ll be able to print out the pages as a permanent keepsake to go with your yearbook.

(Please note: This is a third-party platform that is not sponsored by Caledonia-Mumford Central Schools. Students are signing up as individuals. The school has no responsibility for the platform or content generated on it.)

Yearbooks are in! We know you've been anxious to see the 2020 Ainodelac and it is finally here.
You may pick up your copy during the times below:
Tuesday, June 9, 2020, in the MIDDLE SCHOOL LOOP between 3 p.m. and 6 p.m.

Juniors: 3:00-3:30 pm
Sophomores: 3:30-4:00
Freshmen: 4:00-4:30
8th Grade: 4:30-5:00
7th Grade: 5:00-5:30
6th Grade: 5:30-6:00

Siblings in different grades may pick theirs up at the same time, and if you can’t make the allotted time for your class, you may come during a later time slot. Yearbooks will also be available for pick-up on Wednesday from 10 am-2 pm in the middle school office.
There are a few extra yearbooks available for purchase—stop by during pickup or call 538-3482 to reserve one.

post_text:
If you have NOT mailed your ballot for the Tuesday, June 9, 2020 school budget vote (and board of education candidates), today is likely the last possible day to do so, in order for it to arrive by U.S. mail at the school by Tuesday.
If you do NOT get your preaddressed/postage paid envelope containing your ballot into the U.S. mail today, we will have a secure container outside of the District Office building on Tuesday only, where you may deposit your ballot/envelope.

Reminders regarding the Budget Vote:
1. Read the instructions for filling out the ballot.
2. Completely fill in the bubbles next to your choice.
3. Sign the envelope. IMPORTANT! Unsigned envelopes are a voided vote!
4. Return the ballot today, Friday, June 5 by mail, or drop off on Tuesday, June 9 at the container outside of the District Office.
5. Ballots must be received by 5 p.m., Tuesday, June 9 to count.
6. If you need an absentee ballot, contact Terry Hasseler at 585-538-3401 or email thasseler@cal-mum.org.
Thank you!

Every year the high school chorus honors the seniors at the spring concert with a slideshow of photos from their childhood to their senior year of high school. The slideshow is played while the chorus sings a song.
Unfortunately, the Class of 2020 did not get their own slideshow, but instead of bypassing the beloved tradition, Senior Sophia Bazzett, with cooperation from the other senior chorus members, created a slideshow for everyone to enjoy. Accompanying the slideshow is the song that the chorus would have performed at their final high school concert, under the direction of Mr. Todd Walker.
Congratulations Class of 2020!

post_text:
In accordance with Gov. Andrew Cuomo's executive order, the annual school budget vote and board of education election, will be done by absentee ballot only.
You will receive an envelope in the mail that contains an informational postcard, an official ballot and a self-addressed, stamped return envelope.
Completed ballots must be received (via U.S. mail) at the district office no later than June 9, 2020.
A secured touchless container will be placed outside of the district office on June 9 ONLY to accept ballots that were not mailed in time to be received via U.S. Mail.
The Cal-Mum Chronicle Budget Newsletter will be mailed out on May 27, 2020 with complete details.
The June 2, 2020 Annual Budget Hearing to present the proposed $18,796,774 budget will be held virtually via Zoom. The public may view and participate in the meeting. A link to the Zoom meeting will be posted to the school website on June 2, 20202.
Find complete details on all of this and the budget on our school website https://www.cal-mum.org/Page/2126

post_text: How about a round of applause for our 5th grader Jakob Bishop, Slingshot’s wrestler of the year! We can’t wait to see this guy in a Raider singlet!
shared_text:
Slingshot Wrestling Club
May 9 at 9:45 PM ·

2019-2020 Co-Winner Slingshot Elite - Male Wrestler of the Year - Jakob Bishop

Back-to-back for Jakob! Team leader in wins this year with 44, he had 24 pins & won a whopping 6 tournaments. He finished 2nd at the NYWAY Western Regional, but only because the state champ happens to be in our region. Jakob went toe to toe with him in a 6-3 loss. NY Youth Wrestling ranked Jakob #2 in NY in the final rankings. Though we’re disappointed we couldn’t see him at States, he had an amazing year. Jakob is the model of diligence, working hard in practice both in Caledonia & at our club. He also puts in lots of work in the offseason. It’ll be fun to see what he becomes when he enters the varsity scene in a few years. Congrats Jakob! A well-deserved award!

📸 Danette DeNoto

It’ll be fun to see what he becomes when he enters the varsity scene in a few years. Congrats Jakob! A well-deserved award!

📸 Danette DeNoto

The quarantine gives us the perfect opportunity to carve out a brief time to complete the U.S. Census.
Livingston County’s goal remains to ensure that all residents are counted during the 2020 Census. A full count will ensure the allocation of Federal funding to resources, programs and organizations that directly affect our school and community. (First Responder resources, school lunch programs, road improvements, and much more!)
Complete the U.S Census you received in the mail or go online to complete it at https://my2020census.gov/.
Be sure you and your family are counted in the 2020 U.S. Census.

Parents: During this period of school closure we have used our Blackboad Mass Notification system more than ever. This system is very effective however, we know that there are some email servers that are placing Cal-Mum School emails sent using the Blackboard Mass Notification system, into your spam folder. Yahoo email seems to be particularly affected by this.
If you think that you are not receiving emails from the Blackboard system, please email ssantora@cal-mum.org so we can help you.
This does NOT affect emails sent to you directly from our Cal-Mum email system, i.e. from a teacher, superintendent, principal, etc. Those are working correctly.
If you are not sure - email ssantora@cal-mum.org!

post_text:
Prior to school closing in mid-March, the Avon Lions Club came to the elementary school health office to do free vision checks for our youngest students. The program is called SEE, Screening Eyes Early and it screens for vision problems related to Amblyopia, commonly referred to as “lazy eye.”
We thank Avon Lions Steve Coleman, Paul & Marcia Andres, Don Martin and CM Elementary School nurse Jennifer Nusbickel for providing this valuable service to our students.

post_text: Congratulations Senior Vincent Molisani
shared_text:
Livingston County News
April 5 at 11:59 AM ·

BIG GAME PERFORMER: Congratulations to Cal-Mum senior Vin Molisani on earning this year's 2019-20 LCN Player of the Year after guiding the Red Raiders to back-to-back sectional titles while finishing 22-3 on the season. Vin became the all-time scoring leader in Cal-Mum history this season with 1,605 points while earning Class C3 MVP honors as well. He averaged 22 points and six rebounds per game Like Dansville's Grace Rittenhouse for the girls, Molisani also earned LCN POY honors last year as well.

LCN Photo by Doug McFarland
